import java.util.*;

public class SerializeDeserializeBinaryTree {
    // TreeNode definition
    static class TreeNode {
        int val;
        TreeNode left;
        TreeNode right;
        TreeNode(int x) { val = x; }
    }

    // Serialize method
    public String serialize(TreeNode root) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        serializeHelper(root, sb);
        return sb.toString();
    }
    
    private void serializeHelper(TreeNode node, StringBuilder sb) {
        if (node == null) {
            sb.append("#,");
            return;
        }
        sb.append(node.val).append(",");
        serializeHelper(node.left, sb);
        serializeHelper(node.right, sb);
    }

    // Deserialize method
    public TreeNode deserialize(String data) {
        Queue<String> nodes = new LinkedList<>(Arrays.asList(data.split(",")));
        return deserializeHelper(nodes);
    }
    
    private TreeNode deserializeHelper(Queue<String> nodes) {
        String val = nodes.poll();
        if (val.equals("#")) {
            return null;
        }
        TreeNode node = new TreeNode(Integer.parseInt(val));
        node.left = deserializeHelper(nodes);
        node.right = deserializeHelper(nodes);
        return node;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SerializeDeserializeBinaryTree solution = new SerializeDeserializeBinaryTree();
        
        // Construct a sample tree
        TreeNode root = new TreeNode(1);
        root.left = new TreeNode(2);
        root.right = new TreeNode(3);
        root.right.left = new TreeNode(4);
        root.right.right = new TreeNode(5);
        
        // Serialize and Deserialize
        String serialized = solution.serialize(root);
        System.out.println("Serialized tree: " + serialized);
        
        TreeNode deserializedRoot = solution.deserialize(serialized);
        System.out.println("Deserialized tree root value: " + deserializedRoot.val);
    }
}

This Java code illustrates how to convert a binary tree into a string (serialization) and then reconstruct it back into a tree (deserialization). 

The `TreeNode` class defines the basic structure of a node in a binary tree, with each node containing an integer value (`val`) and pointers to its left and right children (`left` and `right`). 

The `serialize` method transforms the binary tree into a string representation. It uses a helper method, `serializeHelper`, to traverse the tree in a pre-order fashion (visit root, then left subtree, then right subtree). During traversal, if a node is `null`, it adds a special marker (`#`) to indicate the absence of a node, followed by a comma. For non-null nodes, it appends the nodeâ€™s value followed by a comma, and recursively processes the left and right subtrees.

The `deserialize` method reconstructs the tree from the string representation. It splits the string into individual elements and uses a queue to process them. The `deserializeHelper` method reads values from the queue to build the tree. If it encounters the special marker (`#`), it creates a `null` node. Otherwise, it creates a new `TreeNode` with the given value, then recursively constructs the left and right subtrees.

In the `main` method, a sample tree is created, serialized into a string, and then deserialized back into a tree. The results are printed to verify the correctness of the serialization and deserialization processes.
